In [3]:
for col in gasoline.columns:
    if col not in ["Quarter", "Unleaded Gasoline Sale (UGS)"]:
        gasoline[col] = pd.to_numeric(gasoline[col].astype(str).str.replace(' ','').str.replace(',','.'), errors='ignore')
    elif col == "Unleaded Gasoline Sale (UGS)":
        gasoline[col] = pd.to_numeric(gasoline[col].astype(str).str.replace(' ','').str.replace(',','.'), errors='coerce')

The data show a pattern with a decreasing trend and some seasonality. As expected from a quarterly data, the periods with a length of four show similarity.

Although it can be said just by visual inspection that the data are not stationary with respect to mean, the variance seems to be stationary.

In [7]:
gasoline_tr = gasoline[:28]
lags = [i for i in range(24)]
acorrs = [gasoline_tr["UGS"].autocorr(lag=lag) for lag in lags]

plt.bar(lags,acorrs)
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Correlation values are high for lags that are multiples of four, which indicates a quarter is similar to its counterpart in another year. So it would be convenient to add regressors for quarters to the model.

There are high correlations between the target variable and NLPG, PU, PG, NUGV, NDGV and GNP_Agriculture. They may share the trend and seasonality effects, however. So it might be convenient to also consider the correlations -and also cross-correlations with different lag values- between the input variables with not the target variable but the residuals of the base model. Also all these input variables have high correlations between each other ass well -all higher than 0.6. This is except for all the above input variables and GNP_Agriculture. Therefore for each of the above input variables -except GNP_Agriculture, we may try three possibilities: include only that input variable, include it with GNP_Agriculture and do not include it to the model. Finally, there is a possibility to include only GNP_Agriculture.

Considering the values and the pairwise scatter plots, only the RNUV seems to have a high correlation with the residuals. So we may pick all these columns as candidates to be included in the final model. As mentioned, we also need to check the cross correlations.

def crossCorr(df, target, max_lag):
    lagged_correlation = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(
        {x: [df[target].corr(df[x].shift(-t)) for t in range(max_lag+1)] for x in df.columns})
    return lagged_correlation

base_regressors = ["trend", "Q1", "Q2", "Q3", "Q4"]
scores = {}
for regs in regressors_to_check:
    regressors = base_regressors + regs
    if 'UGS_lag2' in regs:
        i = 2
    elif 'RNUV_lag1' in regs:
        i = 1
    else:
        i = 0
    X = gasoline_tr[i:][regressors]
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    y = gasoline_tr[i:]["UGS"]
    model = sm.OLS(y, X)
    fitted = model.fit()
    parameter_names = ""
    for reg in regs:
        parameter_names += reg + "__"
    scores[parameter_names[:-2]] = fitted.rsquared_adj
    print(regressors)
    print(fitted.summary())
    print("\n --------- \n")

The adjusted R^2 values are pretty close. Yet, as can be seen above, some models such as those with the additional regressors/regressor pairs GNP_Agriculture, PUGNP_Agriculture, PU, NUGVGNP_Agriculture, PG__GNP_Agriculture and PG provide only a small increase on what is obtained by only the trend and the seasonality components. NUGV even made it worse.

The most promising models in terms of their adjusted R^2 values are the models with -except the trend and seasonality input variables- NLPGGNP_Agriculture, NLPG, RNUV_lag1, RNUVRNUV_lag1. Addition of GNP_Agriculture to the model with NLPG improved the score slightly, however the p value associated with the additional input variable, namely GNP_Agriculture, is high. This indicates that GNP_Agriculture does not explain a significant proportion of the variance. As the scores are obtained on the same dataset that the models are built on, we have the risk of overfitting. So rejecting to add GNP_Agriculture input variable to the model with NLPG could be more proper in these circumstances.

Another promising model is the one with RNUV_lag1 as addition to trend and seasonality. Again, the difference in score is negligible. The relationship between RNUV_lag1, some value proportional to the number of unleaded gasoline using vehicles joined to the traffic a quarter ago, and the target variable, unleaded gasoline sales, seems more meaningful than that of NLPG, the number of LPG using vehicles. So the former is less likely to suffer from an issue like a "correlated yet non-causal" relationship.

So it is chosen as the final model. Let us see it once more to evaluate it further.

The residuals does not show a pattern that reveal itself easily by visual inspection. Though skewed, the shape of the histogram seems like a normal distribution curve. The mean is almost equal to zero. The qq plot seems to indicate a normal distribution also. These are pretty much compatible with the assumptions of the linear regression.
